    "## Checking data null bias"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%% md\n"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "You will need to check the bias in your data sometimes and some forms of bias checking are to be done manually but our package offers two forms of automated bias checking. To find columns with too much missing data and to check to see if the distribution of discrete data is as intended. <br>\n",
    "Here, we have checked the columns for too much missing data, in other words, columns that have too many null values. This is done using the ``check_bias`` function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%%\n"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [

     ]

    }

    "For this you can either remove the column with too many null values which is done later in this example file, or you can impute the missing data using the ``handle_null`` function which also gives the option to remove the rows with the missing values.<br>\n",
    "Here, we have removed the row with null values in columns that had too many nulls."
   ]

    "# make copy of unhandled version for future use\n",
    "dm_uncleaned = dm.copy()\n",
    "\n",
    "# remove rows with null values from columns that have too many nulls\n",
    "for null in too_null_1[0]:\n",
    "    dm = da.handle_null(dm, null[0], impute_type=\"remove\")\n",
    "dm.head()"
   ]

    "## Change data type"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%% md\n"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "You can change a column's data type between <strong>String, Integer and Float</strong> types using the ``change_type`` function. <br>\n",
    "Here we have changed <strong><em>BMRKR1</em></strong> from float to int."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%%\n"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dm_uncleaned = da.change_type(dm_uncleaned, 'BMRKR1', int)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%% md\n"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "## Add a numeric coded column from a categorical column"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%% md\n"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "The ``categorical_to_numeric`` function changes numerical data columns to categorical ones. Here we changed the <strong><em>SEX</em></strong> column in the <strong><em>dm_uncleaned</em></strong> dataset to 0 and 1 and added the values into a separate column (<em>SEX_goup</em>) by setting add to True, if we use False it will replace the previous values within the SEX column."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {
    "pycharm": {
     "name": "#%%\n"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dm_uncleaned = da.categorical_to_numeric(dm_uncleaned, 'SEX', [['F', 0],['M', 1]], True)"
   ]

    "## Plotting the relationship between some cloumns"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",

     "name": "#%% md\n"

   "source": [
    "You can plot the relationship between columns using the ``relation`` function. It will return one or two heatmaps depending on the input. For categorical data, it will plot a heatmap of <strong><em>chi-square</em></strong> values. For numerical data, it will show the <strong><em>correlation</em></strong>. <br>\n",
    "Here, we have removed columns with too many null values and have used the ``data-selection`` function to select some columns to plot and then plotted the relationship heatmaps."
   ]
